tered distribution of sites in coastal areas as well as in inland areas, even when we consider the rel-
atively high number of multi-layered sites in this group. This means that during the LGM, Early
Iberomaurusian occupation intensity was probably very low. The Late Iberomaurusian seems to
experience a relative increase of human activity when compared to the earlier phase. Although
site distribution is still very dispersed, more regions with more intense settlement activity can be
identified. The Eastern Rif and the coastal regions are occupied more homogeneously, while the
settlement remains scattered in other areas. The general increase of sites fromEarly to Late Ibero-
maurusian and the appearance of some strong clusters is particularly notable.
The site density analyses show clear differences in land use pattern over time and space in
Iberia. In the North, settlement expands and becomes more homogeneous through time, while
it is more constricted in the South. In North-West Africa, settlement structure is very dis-
persed with low site density and gets more stable only in the Late Iberomaurusian; this differ-
ence to Southern Iberia will be subject to further discussion.
